=== History ===
=== Foundation ===
The date of foundation is unknown. According to shrine tradition, it was founded around the reign of the 10th emperor, {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|qid=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}<ref name="歴史">[https://web.archive.org/web/20160129181104/http://www.geocities.jp/mizokuijinja/sub2.html History and Sacred Treasures] (official website).</ref>. As noted in the section on enshrined deities, this shrine worships the lineage of {{ill|lt=Kamotake-tsunumi-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Mishima Mizokui Mimi}}, and its relationship with traditions found in the {{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}} and {{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}} has been pointed out.

In the Kojiki account of Emperor Jimmu, {{ill|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi-no-Kami|1=Ōmononushi}} falls in love with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Seyadatara-hime|1=UNKNOWN}} (Tamaki-hime), the daughter of Mishima Mizokui, transforms into a vermilion-painted arrow, and strikes the maiden’s genitals. Though startled, she places the arrow by her bed, whereupon it turns into a handsome man, and from their union is born Futo-tatara Isuzu-ki-hime-no-Mikoto (Himetatara Isuzuhime-no-Mikoto).

In the Age of the Gods volume of the Nihon Shoki, it is written that Himetatara Isuzuhime-no-Mikoto was the child of the Ōmiwa deity, and that {{ill|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Kami|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} transformed into an eight-fathom crocodile and visited Mishima Mizokui-hime (Tamaki-hime), producing Himetatara Isuzuhime-no-Mikoto, who later became the consort of {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|qid=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}. A similar account appears in the Nihon Shoki entry for the 16th day of the 8th month of the year of Emperor Jimmu’s accession, where Tamaki-hime is described as the daughter of Mishima Mizokui Mimi-no-Mikoto.

Based on these texts, and noting that within the shrine precincts Kotoshironushi-no-Kami is enshrined rather than Ōmononushi-no-Kami, some theories point to interaction between the local earth-deity lineage of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kamo clan|1=UNKNOWN}} that worshipped Kotoshironushi and the Mishima power group<ref name="神々"/>{{efn|Although Kotoshironushi is described as a child of Ōkuninushi of Izumo, one theory in *Nihon no Kamigami* suggests that Kotoshironushi was originally of Kamo lineage rather than Izumo.}}. In the surrounding area remain shrines such as {{ill|lt=Mishima Kamo Shrine|Q11355295|qid=Q11355295|1=Mishima-Kamo Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Kamo Shrine (Takatsuki City)|Q11675604|qid=Q11675604|lt=Kamo Shrine|1=Kamo Shrine (Q11675604)}}, as well as place names like Kamomura and Kamobayashi, suggesting the influence of either the heavenly or earthly Kamo lineage. {{要出典範囲|There is also a theory that these interactions were later reconstructed into the myths of the Kojiki and Nihon Shoki, emphasizing Izumo deities as described above|date=November 2020}}.

From the view that “mizo” symbolizes water and “mimi” represents length, another theory holds that this lineage was involved in irrigation related to the {{ill|lt=Ai River|Q11450512|qid=Q11450512|1=Ai River}} system<ref name="神々"/>.

=== Historical outline ===
According to shrine tradition, the area once contained the {{ill|lt=field allotment|Q11381648|qid=Q11381648|1=land}} of {{ill|lt=Prince Abo|Q11657231|qid=Q11657231|1=Prince Abo}}, son of {{ill|lt=Emperor Heijō|Q353558|qid=Q353558|1=Emperor Heizei}}. During a drought in the {{ill|lt=Tencho|Q1373138|qid=Q1373138|1=Tenchō}} era ({{ill|lt=824|Q30353|qid=Q30353|1=824}}–{{ill|lt=834|Q30381|qid=Q30381|1=834}}), the prince petitioned the court and received a mirror, with which he prayed for rain; heavy rain then fell<ref name="地名">“Osaka Prefecture Place Names,” entry on Mizokui Shrine.</ref>. The sacred treasure known as the “Dawn Sacred Mirror” (a bronze mirror with two deities and two beasts) is said to be that mirror.

In the {{ill|lt=Engi Shiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, compiled in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), the shrine is listed as “Mizokui Shrine, Shimashimo District, Settsu Province,” and is thus counted as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

In ancient times, there was an “Upper Shrine” about 500 meters to the northeast (present-day Gakuenchō, Ibaraki City) where Himetatara Isuzuhime-no-Mikoto was enshrined, while the current precincts were known as the “Lower Shrine,” enshrining Tamaki-hime-no-Mikoto<ref name="神々">*Nihon no Kamigami*, entry on Mizokui Shrine.</ref>. The period when they were separated is unclear, but medieval documents from {{ill|lt=Kakitsu|Q1193238|qid=Q1193238|1=Kakitsu}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1441|Q6402|qid=Q6402|1=1441}}) mention place names of Upper Shrine and Lower Shrine<ref name="神々"/>. The Lower Shrine is considered the original Shikinaisha<ref name="神々"/>, and until their merger in Meiji 42, rituals were conducted at both shrines. Shiga Tsuyoshi, in *Research on Shikinaisha*, suggests that in ancient times the Lower Shrine’s Tamakushi-hime served the Upper Shrine’s Mizokui Mimi-no-Mikoto, but after Isuzu-hime became Empress of Emperor Jimmu, the mother deity gained prominence and the Lower Shrine was elevated to Shikinaisha status.

The shrine buildings were rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Bunmei|Q1193544|qid=Q1193544|1=Bunmei}} 9 ({{ill|lt=1477|Q6614|qid=Q6614|1=1477}}) by the local lord Mizokui Hyōgo-no-suke Sadanobu, and again during the {{ill|lt=Bunroku|Q1373039|qid=Q1373039|1=Bunroku}} era ({{ill|lt=1592|Q6769|qid=Q6769|1=1592}}–{{ill|lt=1596|Q6785|qid=Q6785|1=1596}}) by Hasegawa Shikibu-shōyū. The current buildings date from {{ill|lt=Kanpō|Q1145798|qid=Q1145798|1=Kanpō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1742|Q7575|qid=Q7575|1=1742}}), constructed by Komeya Uemon and {{ill|lt=Sawano Tsuru|Q7428583|qid=Q7428583|lt=Komeya Kibei|1=Sawanotsuru}}. Until the Meiji Restoration, the precincts also contained a Shingon temple, Fudō-in Myōren-ji, as the shrine-temple complex.

In {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5), under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, the shrine was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}, and in {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|qid=Q2048|1=1907}} (Meiji 40) it was designated as a shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and paper offerings. In {{ill|lt=1909|Q2057|qid=Q2057|1=1909}} (Meiji 42), three deities enshrined at Mizokui Upper Shrine east of the Ai River—Himetatara Isuzuhime-no-Mikoto, Mizokui Mimi-no-Mikoto, and Ame-no-Hikata-Kushi-Hikata-no-Mikoto—were merged here. In the same year, the Tenman Shrine (Sugawara no Michizane) from Nikaidō Hoshimi was merged into the grounds, and in {{ill|lt=1910|Q2075|qid=Q2075|1=1910}} (Meiji 43) the Arakami Shrine (Kagutsuchi-no-Kami, Nakatsuhiko-no-Kami, Nakatsuhime-no-Kami) from Megaki was also relocated to the precincts.

In {{ill|lt=1941|Q5231|qid=Q5231|1=1941}} (Shōwa 16), the shrine was promoted to {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q134917326|lt=Fusha|1=Fu-sha}} status.

