=== Associated shrines ===
* Kotoshironushi Shrine
** Enshrined deities: {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|qid=Q8009611}}, {{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi-no-Kami|UNKNOWN|lt=Kagu-tsuchi-no-Kami}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Okutsuhiko-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Okutsuhime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mitsuhanome-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Haniyasubiko-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Haniyasubime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}
:: Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto is the husband deity of Tamaki-hime-no-Mikoto. During the Meiji period, the deities of Megaki Village were merged here.

=== Minor shrines ===
* Amaterasu Ōmikami Shrine – Enshrined deities: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|1=Amaterasu|qid=Q455602}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sarutahiko-no-Kami|1=Sarutahiko Ōkami|qid=Q3090037}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
* Uke-mochi Shrine – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Uke Mochi-no-Kami|Q2280323|qid=Q2280323|1=Ukemochi}}
* Tajikarao Shrine – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Tajikarao|UNKNOWN|lt=Tajikarao-no-Kami}}
* Konohana Sakuya-hime Shrine – Enshrined deities: {{ill|lt=Konohana Sakuya-hime|UNKNOWN|lt=Konohana Sakuya-hime-no-Kami}}, {{ill|lt=Shinatsuhiko|Q1073925|qid=Q1073925|lt=Shinatsuhiko-no-Kami|1=Shinatsuhiko}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ichikishima-hime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}

On April 23, 1909 (Meiji 42), the Tenman Shrine of Nikaidō Hoshimi was merged into the Ichikishima Shrine.

=== Festivals ===
* Monthly Festival (1st of every month)
* New Year’s Day Festival (January 1)
* Tondo Festival (January 15)
* Setsubun Festival (February 3)
* Inari Festival (second Sunday of April)
* Ancestral Spirit Festival (Ryōsen Festival) (April 13 → April 11) – Noh performances were once dedicated. <ref name="社史">Ambo Yukihiko, “History of Mizokui Shrine,” Mizokui Shrine Support Association</ref>
* Arakami Festival (third Sunday of April)
* Spring Grand Festival (May 5)
* Autumn Grand Festival (October 14)
* Shichi-Go-San (November 15)
* Fire-Quelling Festival (December 10)
* Great Purification Festival (December 31)

In the past, based on the episode in the Nihon Shoki (Age of the Gods, upper volume) in which Kotoshironushi-no-Kami visited Mishima Mizokui-hime, a joint procession was held on the same day with Mishima Kamo Shrine, which also enshrines Kotoshironushi-no-Kami<ref>“Osaka Prefecture Place Names,” entry on Mishima Kamo Shrine.</ref>.

=== Sacred treasures ===
* Dawn Sacred Mirror  
According to shrine tradition, this mirror was used by Prince Abo during prayers for rain. It is a bronze mirror from China’s Han dynasty, decorated with two deities and two beasts<ref name="歴史"/>.

=== Excavated pottery ===
In 1939 (Shōwa 14), during river improvement works on the Ai River, large quantities of {{ill|lt=Haji ware|Q5639938|qid=Q5639938|1=Haji pottery}} and {{ill|lt=Sue ware|Q7634351|qid=Q7634351|1=Sue pottery}} were excavated from land adjacent to the former Mizokui Upper Shrine, and records show they were kept at Mizokui Shrine<ref name="社史">Ambo Yukihiko, “History of Mizokui Shrine,” Mizokui Shrine Support Association</ref>.

The site of the former Upper Shrine and its surroundings constitute the “'''Mizokui Archaeological Site'''.” In excavations conducted in 1997 (Heisei 9) by the {{ill|lt=Public Interest Incorporated Foundation|Q40734470|qid=Q40734470|1=public interest incorporated foundation}} {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefectural Cultural Properties Center|Q11425913|qid=Q11425913|1=Buried cultural property center}} (formerly the Osaka Prefectural Cultural Properties Research Center), remains were discovered including {{ill|lt=small-plot paddy fields|Q86743587|qid=Q86743587|1=small-plot paddy fields}} from the {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|qid=Q459939|1=Kofun period}}, artifacts from the {{ill|lt=Nara period|Q189178|qid=Q189178|1=Nara period}} and {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, and square-section structural remains believed to be the former Mizokui Upper Shrine from the latter half of the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|qid=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}}<ref>[https://www.occh.or.jp/?s=data/setumeikai Osaka Prefectural Cultural Properties Center] 1997</ref>.

=== Related sites ===
[[File:Mizokui 101.JPG|200px|thumb|right|Monument marking the former Mizokui Upper Shrine]]
* Former site of Mizokui Upper Shrine (Gakuenchō, Ibaraki City, {{ウィキ座標|34|49|02.64|N|135|35|25.28|E|region:JP-27_type:landmark|location|name=Upper Shrine Site (monument)}})
: The site of the former Upper Shrine, marked by a stone monument. It was erected in April 1965 (Shōwa 40) when Naniwa Commercial High School built an athletic field on the site.

* {{ill|lt=Mishima Kamo Shrine|Q11355295|qid=Q11355295|1=Mishima-Kamo Shrine}}

: A shrine in Takatsuki City located across the Ai River. The crest of Mishima Kamo Shrine can be seen on stone lanterns within Mizokui Shrine’s grounds. According to tradition, portable shrine processions from Mishima Kamo Shrine to Mizokui Shrine began in Genroku 10 (1697) and continued until the Meiji period.

=== Visitor information ===
; Address
* 9-21 Isuzuchō, {{ill|lt=Ibaraki City|Q502403|qid=Q502403|1=Ibaraki, Osaka}}, Osaka Prefecture

; Access
* From {{ill|lt=Ibaraki Station|Q1072931|qid=Q1072931|1=Ibaraki Station}} ({{ill|lt=West Japan Railway Company|Q502125|qid=Q502125|lt=JR West|1=West Japan Railway Company}}) East Exit or {{ill|lt=Ibaraki-shi Station|Q3969806|qid=Q3969806|1=Ibaraki-shi Station}} ({{ill|lt=Hankyu Corporation|Q473058|qid=Q473058|1=Hankyu}}) South Exit, take the {{ill|lt=Kintetsu Bus|Q18636319|qid=Q18636319|1=Kintetsu Bus}} (Route 84 Kuwata–Hirata Loop) and get off at “Kuwata-chō” bus stop; about a 4-minute walk east after disembarking.

